repertoires. As the range of Indian food grows in Australia, chefs have the liberty of defining their version of Indian food. Newer Indian restaurants, like Delhi Streets and Gopi Ka Chatka both in Melbourne, have done away with a regional focus and now present street food or â€˜chaatsâ€™ such as bhel puri (puffed rice with assorted lentils and chutney) and pani puri (ball-shaped crispy shell filled with a mixture of tamarind chutney, potato, onion or chickpea) in a casual environment. Start the party with pani puri shots. Add tequila for an extra kick ğŸ’¥ #saumaperth A post shared by  Sauma (@saumaperth) on Jul 16, 2020 at 2:06am PDT This shift is also clear at higher end restaurants, like Sauma in Perth. Owner Gurps Bagga describes his food as regional Indian cuisine, with local Australian flavours. â€œOur food here is distinctly South Indian, a bit of Goan and Keralan inspired but it is also innovative and local,â€ he says. For example, Bagga uses WAâ€™s hardwood sawdust mushrooms and cooks it with garlic, korma sauce, chilli oil and hazelnut truffle. â€œYou can taste the Indian spices but Iâ€™ve added my own touch to it. You can call it modern, you can call it fusion. The important thing is that you think itâ€™s tasty.â€ And that, just might be the unofficial ethos of Indian food.